textBeforeTable: Below is the table of summary conference statistics (including a thumb of the matrix I used to calculate "r") and a cat photo -  TABLE AND CAT PHOTO: A few relationships even showed very slight negative correlation; Attempts / Yards Per Attempt (r=-0.29), Attempts / Yards Per Completion (r=-0.29) and Completions / Yards Per Completion (r=-0.26) Two relationships showed a relatively meager positive correlation; Completions / Completion % (r=0.37) and Yards / Yards Per Completion (r=0.36) Yards / Yards Per Attempt – r=0.49 Yards Per Attempt / Comp. % - r=0.57 Attempts / Yards – r=0.65 Completions / Yards – r=0.77 Yards Per Attempt / Yards Per Completion – r=0.82 Completions / Attempts - r=0.88 The six most correlated variables are as follows – RESULTS: Fifteen potential relationships were examined and their r-value calculated. So, in all (n=144 for each variable), there were 864 individual values which were either reported or calculated from existing data. The assumption made was that 144 trials would be sufficient to show some interrelationships inside the data. A matrix of statistics was created using six variables – passing attempt, pass completions, total passing yards, yards per attempt, yards per completion and completion percentage. For purposes of this diary, interception data was not included, but is part of a future planned diary along this vein of discussion.
